entry.title: [omnibox][cr23] Fix action chip color for high-contrast / themed clients
entry.content:
In addition to those clients who are eligible for the full CR2023 color

treatment, there exists a subset of clients who are not eligible for the

CR2023 colors even though they have enabled the ChromeRefresh2023 flag.

In particular, those clients who utilize high-contrast mode and/or a

custom theme will not be eligible for the usual CR2023 color mappings.



This CL introduces a set of color tokens and mappings which will ensure

that all clients are presented with reasonable colors for the action

chip irrespective of whether or not they're using high-contrast mode

and/or a custom theme. Without this fix, the action chip renders in an

opaque black (or white) color when the user attempts to hover/select it.



As noted below, this CL will only affect clients who enable CR2023 and

are using high-contrast mode and/or a custom theme. All other clients

will remain unaffected by the changes in this CL.

entry.title: Workaround for 3PCB when rendering sandboxed media
entry.content:
When 3PCB is enabled, access-controlled media URLs that

are served with "Content-Security-Policy: sandbox" will be

broken when it is loaded as the top-level URL.



This includes static media types where there is little privacy

or security risk to allowing cookies to be send for the data

request when the media is being loaded as the top-level document.



The CL patches this by overriding Document::SiteForCookies in these

specific cases. To be cautious, this is only done in the

MediaDocumentParser.

entry.title: Web-expose BrowserCaptureMediaStreamTrack on Android
entry.content:
This interface has been shipped by default since m104,

because the runtime-enabled flag it's been behind has been

default-enabled for all platforms other than Android since then.

This CL removes the flag from the interface, thereby Web-exposing

the interface on Android, too. The motivation for this change is

that BrowserCaptureMediaStreamTrack is now required when

either Region Capture or Element Capture are enabled.

The alternative is to produce a hybrid flag that would be

implied by both the RegionCapture and ElementCapture flags,

but this complexity would not confer any benefits.

entry.title: [rebaseline-cl] Warn about builds with unrelated `FAILURE`s
entry.content:
https://crrev.com/c/4808257 relaxed the builders-without-results check

too much. There are actually two cases where a build may have

Buildbucket's `FAILURE` status without web test failures:

1. Only unrelated test failures (fixed in the aforementioend patch).

From `rebaseline-cl`'s perspective, this build can be treated as

present but successful. The user does not need to retry the build.

2. Failed for reasons other than tests (e.g., compile, merging results,

etc). This is currently incorrectly treated as all-pass, when such

builds need to be retried.



To distinguish these cases, `rebaseline-cl` needs to look at the failure

reason emitted by the recipe, and upgrade FAILURE -> INFRA_FAILURE for

case (2).

entry.title: webdialogs: remove OnDialogClosingFromKeyEvent()
entry.content:
This method was only overridden in one place, where it was used to call

OnDialogClosed() unnecessarily - in that situation, the dialog is just

about to close anyway, so OnDialogClosed() is about to be run by

WebDialogDelegate itself. This change deletes the method, its only

override, and its only call site. Simplification of

PrintPreviewDialogController as a result might be possible, since it no

longer needs to tolerate multiple calls to OnDialogClosed().



This change does not add an automated test. I tried to do so, but:

* A unit test that doesn't depend on Views didn't work: there's no way

to send key events to the dialog directly without Views APIs;

* A unit test that does depend on Views required putting a single unit

test for this code, which otherwise doesn't use Views, in a different

part of the source tree, which seems very ugly;

* A non-unit test that doesn't depend on Views would need to be an

interactive ui test so that it could use ui_controls::SendKeyPress().

Given the cost of interactive ui tests, how flaky they generally are,

and the low risk of this code regressing in the future, this seems not

worth writing.



Instead, I manually tested that I did not regress the behavior.

SessionStateAnimatorImpl::AnimationSequence could be destructed

prematurely when LayerCopyAnimator aborts animations due to container

bounds change during animation setup. On an edge case with multiple

displays, this could happen to containers in one display but not

the other. As a result, the animations that are not aborted would

hit use-after-free. This CL defers the animation completed signal

until EndSequence is called so that the animation sequence would be

kept around when there are pending animations.

entry.title: Printing: Implement intervals for printer status querying
entry.content:
- This CL updates the existing logic of querying every printer on a

fixed interval.

- Below is the logic used for determining the delay between printer queries

+--------------------+------------------+----------------+-------------+

| Time Settings open | # Saved printers | Error printers | Good printers |

+--------------------+------------------+----------------+-------------+

| < 2 min | <= 3 | 10 - 15 sec | 25 - 30 sec |

+--------------------+------------------+----------------+-------------+

| < 2 min | > 3 | 25 - 30 sec | 60 - 80 sec |

+--------------------+------------------+----------------+-------------+

| > 2 min | n/a | 45 - 60 sec | 60 - 80 sec |

+--------------------+------------------+----------------+-------------+

| > 5 min | n/a | No query | No query |

+--------------------+------------------+----------------+-------------+



- Testing was performed manually to ensure each of the above interval

scenarios behaved as expected. This scheduling logic proved to be too

complex to be properly capture in a unit test.

entry.title: Fix ChromeNetworkServiceBrowserTest for Windows network sandbox.
entry.content:
In crrev.com/4985832, this test was re-enabled on Windows.



However, this test was subsequently failing when the Windows

network sandbox was enabled.



This is because, on Windows, network migration must occur in

order to set the right ACLs on the sandbox data files.



If this `trigger_migration` is not set, then a DCHECK hits in

MaybeGrantSandboxAccessToNetworkContextData.



In addition, it was never really safe to have two network

contexts pointing to the same directory, which is what was

happening here, so the test is adjusted to use a completely

different directory for the test network context, underneath

the user data dir.



This should fix this test, on Windows, once and for all!



BUG=868667

entry.title: SAA: Fix permission display with more than one embedded permission
entry.content:
The Android Preference library doesn't like it when the same key is

assigned to multiple preferences. It should be unique. This is

causing issues with embedded permissions and potentially also chooser

permissions.

Fix the issue by keeping the preferences in a list instead of

assigning keys to them.

Also ensure that the icon of embedded permissions is updated

when a permission is blocked.
